going to continue

10
00:00:24,710 --> 00:00:28,180
discussing firm behavior.

11
00:00:28,180 --> 00:00:32,830
But today we're going to deviate
from our fantasy land

12
00:00:32,830 --> 00:00:36,580
of 14.01 to come to the real
world a little bit which is to

13
00:00:36,580 --> 00:00:41,840
talk a bit about whether firms
actually maximize profits.

14
00:00:41,840 --> 00:00:48,190
The whole presumption of
producer theory is just as we

15
00:00:48,190 --> 00:00:51,130
think with consumer theory,
consumers maximize utility.

16
00:00:51,130 --> 00:00:53,570
Except producers maximize
profits.

17
00:00:53,570 --> 00:00:56,190
That turns out to be an
incredibly useful shorthand

18
00:00:56,190 --> 00:00:57,780
for lots of things.

19
00:00:57,780 --> 00:01:00,470
And it will turn out to be,
as with any simplifying

20
00:01:00,470 --> 00:01:05,519
assumption, largely right and
largely will help us draw a

21
00:01:05,519 --> 00:01:08,320
lot of interesting conclusions
about firms and markets.

22
00:01:08,320 --> 00:01:11,550
Nonetheless, it's clearly
not right in

23
00:01:11,550 --> 00:01:14,110
reality for every firm.

24
00:01:14,110 --> 00:01:18,240
For example, we see lots of
firms doing things which look

25
00:01:18,240 --> 00:01:20,940
pretty wasteful like big
corporate jets or

26
00:01:20,940 --> 00:01:22,760
other things like that.

27
00:01:22,760 --> 00:01:26,780
More relevantly, huge pay for
CEOs seems pretty wasteful.

28
00:01:26,780 --> 00:01:30,920
So, for example, on 2004 the net
income of Eli Lilly, the

29
00:01:30,920 --> 00:01:33,800
drug manufacturer,
fell by 29%.

30
00:01:33,800 --> 00:01:38,940
Yet the CEO got a 41% raise to
to $12.5 million a year.

31
00:01:38,940 --> 00:01:42,040
Or even more so in the financial
crisis, in 2009,

32
00:01:42,040 --> 00:01:45,285
Citigroup and Merrill each lost
more than $27 billion.

33
00:01:45,285 --> 00:01:46,830
It's a pretty bad year
for the financial

34
00:01:46,830 --> 00:01:48,390
sector, you might think.

35
00:01:48,390 --> 00:01:52,290
And yet their CEO's pay in each
company rose by more than

36
00:01:52,290 --> 00:01:54,650
10% to about $15 million.

37
00:01:54,650 --> 00:01:59,380
So in the worst year for the
financial system since 1929,

38
00:01:59,380 --> 00:02:02,350
the CEO pay increased in
these two companies.

39
00:02:02,350 --> 00:02:05,610
So you might think that this
sounds kind of off.

40
00:02:05,610 --> 00:02:06,630
How could we explain that?

41
00:02:06,630 --> 00:02:08,789
Well, there's two possible
explanations.

42
00:02:08,789 --> 00:02:10,990
So one explanation is that
things which look wasteful

43
00:02:10,990 --> 00:02:12,280
really aren't.

44
00:02:12,280 --> 00:02:14,510
That is that we pay CEOs a
huge amount of money, but

45
00:02:14,510 --> 00:02:16,070
they're worth it.

46
00:02:16,070 --> 00:02:20,450
So, for example, even at his
ultimate salary of $33 million

47
00:02:20,450 --> 00:02:23,600
per year, Michael Jordan
was vastly underpaid.

48
00:02:23,600 --> 00:02:25,920
By any reasonable economic
analysis of the value he added

49
00:02:25,920 --> 00:02:29,410
to the Chicago Bulls, it was
well in excess of $50 million.

50
00:02:29,410 --> 00:02:31,380
So even though he was
paid $33 million,

51
00:02:31,380 --> 00:02:34,020
Michael Jordan was underpaid.

52
00:02:34,020 --> 00:02:35,860
Similarly, just because someone
gets paid a lot of

53
00:02:35,860 --> 00:02:37,830
money, doesn't mean that
they're overpaid.

54
00:02:37,830 --> 00:02:39,840
These CEOs are very
talented people.

55
00:02:39,840 --> 00:02:41,090
They may be underpaid.

56
00:02:41,090 --> 00:02:43,750
Now this is an argument you
might have made with a

57
00:02:43,750 --> 00:02:45,930
somewhat straight face maybe
10 or 15 years ago.

58
00:02:45,930 --> 00:02:47,890
It's hard to make that with
a straight face now.

59
00:02:47,890 --> 00:02:51,150
It's hard to believe that these
CEOs of these companies

60
00:02:51,150 --> 00:02:53,500
aren't overpaid given their
company performance and even

61
00:02:53,500 --> 00:02:56,340
the kind of facts we
just talked about.

62
00:02:56,340 --> 00:03:00,150
So a better explanation for
things like excessive CEO pay

63
00:03:00,150 --> 00:03:04,340
is something which we call
the agency problem.

64
00:03:04,340 --> 00:03:13,280

65
00:03:13,280 --> 00:03:16,520
And that's what I want to
emphasize in today's lecture.

66
00:03:16,520 --> 00:03:22,000
In reality, we think of a firm
as something where there's a

67
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:23,710
guy who's an owner.

68
00:03:23,710 --> 00:03:25,340
He hires some machines
and some workers.

69
00:03:25,340 --> 00:03:29,110
They make stuff that he thought
of, and you produce

70
00:03:29,110 --> 00:03:31,270
it, and some profit is made.

71
00:03:31,270 --> 00:03:34,110
So the model we have in mind
when we talked about the firms

72
00:03:34,110 --> 00:03:37,720
so far in this course is the
model of what we might call a

73
00:03:37,720 --> 00:03:40,890
sole proprietorship
or a partnership.

74
00:03:40,890 --> 00:03:43,830
It's a model where one
individual, where there's

75
00:03:43,830 --> 00:03:45,640
basically a commonality.

76
00:03:45,640 --> 00:03:47,370
The key thing that we've
discussed so far is a

77
00:03:47,370 --> 00:03:52,240
commonality of interest between
the owners who own the

78
00:03:52,240 --> 00:03:56,740
company and the control
of production.

79
00:03:56,740 --> 00:03:59,710
So the people who earn the money
from the company also

80
00:03:59,710 --> 00:04:01,210
control the production.

81
00:04:01,210 --> 00:04:04,310
So when you start your start-ups
when you graduate,

82
00:04:04,310 --> 00:04:06,370
you will start them as a sole
proprietorship or a

83
00:04:06,370 --> 00:04:09,870
partnership where you own the
company, and you control

84
00:04:09,870 --> 00:04:11,410
what's done.

85
00:04:11,410 --> 00:04:14,815
You're there 18 hours a day
making sure the guys are doing

86
00:04:14,815 --> 00:04:16,570
what they're supposed to do.

87
00:04:16,570 --> 00:04:19,110
And you're who gets the money
if they succeed or lose the

88
00:04:19,110 --> 00:04:21,070
money if they fail.

89
00:04:21,070 --> 00:04:24,120
And that's the model we've had
in mind as we've thought about

90
00:04:24,120 --> 00:04:27,610
corporations or firms
so far in our class.

91
00:04:27,610 --> 00:04:30,230
But, in fact, most production
in the US

92
00:04:30,230 --> 00:04:32,260
doesn't happen that way.

93
00:04:32,260 --> 00:04:35,450
Most production in the US
happens through the guise of

94
00:04:35,450 --> 00:04:36,700
corporations.

95
00:04:36,700 --> 00:04:41,710

96
00:04:41,710 --> 00:04:46,790
Corporations are marked
by a separation of

97
00:04:46,790 --> 00:04:48,600
ownership and control.

98
00:04:48,600 --> 00:04:52,140
What defines a corporation
is a separation of

99
00:04:52,140 --> 00:04:54,240
ownership and control.

100
00:04:54,240 --> 00:04:57,800
The owners of corporations are
the stockholders or what we

101
00:04:57,800 --> 00:05:02,350
call the equity holders, people
who have invested money

102
00:05:02,350 --> 00:05:03,850
in the corporation.

103
00:05:03,850 --> 00:05:05,930
So the owners of the corporation
are its investors,

104
00:05:05,930 --> 00:05:07,380
its stockholders, its
equity holders.

105
00:05:07,380 --> 00:05:09,940

106
00:05:09,940 --> 00:05:13,460
All of you, most of you,
probably somewhere--

107
00:05:13,460 --> 00:05:16,050
if you're Jewish, it's in some
Bar Mitzvah gift you got, if

108
00:05:16,050 --> 00:05:18,250
you're not, it's in some other
gift you got-- probably have

109
00:05:18,250 --> 00:05:21,570
some equity ownership in
something somewhere.

110
00:05:21,570 --> 00:05:22,230
OK.

111
00:05:22,230 --> 00:05:24,360
You maybe have a little bond
which says you own five shares

112
00:05:24,360 --> 00:05:25,830
of GM that someone gave you,
because they thought it'd be

113
00:05:25,830 --> 00:05:27,420
cute or whatever.

114
00:05:27,420 --> 00:05:29,260
That's now worthless, but maybe
some other company.

115
00:05:29,260 --> 00:05:31,810

116
00:05:31,810 --> 00:05:32,590
We're equity holders.

117
00:05:32,590 --> 00:05:35,420
We invest in companies.

118
00:05:35,420 --> 00:05:38,110
But we don't make the
production decision.

119
00:05:38,110 --> 00:05:40,670
The production decision is made
by the firm's managers

120
00:05:40,670 --> 00:05:47,230
who are employees of the owners,
the equity holders.

121
00:05:47,230 --> 00:05:48,910
Now these managers may
have some ownership.

122
00:05:48,910 --> 00:05:50,430
And we'll talk about that
in a little bit.

123
00:05:50,430 --> 00:05:54,090
But, by and large, the primary
ownership of the firm is done

124
00:05:54,090 --> 00:05:56,370
by people who do not control
the everyday decisions of

125
00:05:56,370 --> 00:05:56,990
production.

126
00:05:56,990 --> 00:05:59,260
And it sort of makes sense
it has to be that way.

127
00:05:59,260 --> 00:06:02,830
When a company's as big
as Microsoft, you

128
00:06:02,830 --> 00:06:04,190
couldn't have me.

129
00:06:04,190 --> 00:06:07,570
Somewhere, I'm sure if you add
up my various stock funds I

130
00:06:07,570 --> 00:06:12,830
own, I own 0.000000000001%
of Microsoft.

131
00:06:12,830 --> 00:06:15,500
It'd be crazy to have
me involved with a

132
00:06:15,500 --> 00:06:18,800
0.000000000001% of the
decision making.

133
00:06:18,800 --> 00:06:21,620
I don't know anything about
anything that Microsoft does.

134
00:06:21,620 --> 00:06:23,640
It makes sense that there's a
separation of ownership and

135
00:06:23,640 --> 00:06:26,330
control once companies
get big enough.

136
00:06:26,330 --> 00:06:29,240
But the fact that there is a
separation of ownership and

137
00:06:29,240 --> 00:06:32,630
control can lead to this agency
problem and can lead to

138
00:06:32,630 --> 00:06:36,690
firms not maximizing profits.

139
00:06:36,690 --> 00:06:42,220
So, basically, the point is that
managers care not just

140
00:06:42,220 --> 00:06:44,320
about the profits they
make but also how

141
00:06:44,320 --> 00:06:46,310
happy their life is.

142
00:06:46,310 --> 00:06:49,220
And things which make their life
happy may be things which

143
00:06:49,220 --> 00:06:51,530
aren't profit maximizing.

144
00:06:51,530 --> 00:06:54,850
The managers who are in charge
of production may have their

145
00:06:54,850 --> 00:06:59,410
own agenda that deviates from
profit maximization.

146
00:06:59,410 --> 00:07:02,630
And the problem is it may be
hard to figure that out if

147
00:07:02,630 --> 00:07:04,950
you're the owner of the firm.

148
00:07:04,950 --> 00:07:08,200
So the agency problem is the
first example of a problem

149
00:07:08,200 --> 00:07:11,090
we'll talk about later in the
semester of imperfect

150
00:07:11,090 --> 00:07:12,680
information.

151
00:07:12,680 --> 00:07:18,610
This is the first time we'll
see imperfect information.

152
00:07:18,610 --> 00:07:22,160
We've assumed in our class so
far, and we'll assume in our

153
00:07:22,160 --> 00:07:24,780
class going forward that there's
perfect information

154
00:07:24,780 --> 00:07:27,380
the world, that everyone knows
what stuff costs, that

155
00:07:27,380 --> 00:07:30,540
everyone can shop costlessly
across providers, et cetera.

156
00:07:30,540 --> 00:07:32,800
But, in fact, the world
is marked by imperfect

157
00:07:32,800 --> 00:07:34,780
information.

158
00:07:34,780 --> 00:07:39,070
As an owner of Microsoft, as a
trivial owner of Microsoft, I

159
00:07:39,070 --> 00:07:41,960
don't know for sure that every
Microsoft employee is doing

160
00:07:41,960 --> 00:07:43,630
what's profit maximizing
for the company.

161
00:07:43,630 --> 00:07:45,150
I can't.

162
00:07:45,150 --> 00:07:46,650
It's just impossible
for me to own that.

163
00:07:46,650 --> 00:07:49,050
So that creates an
agency problem.

164
00:07:49,050 --> 00:07:52,340
And the agency problem arises
because it's in the employees'

165
00:07:52,340 --> 00:07:53,970
interest, perhaps, to do things
which aren't profit

166
00:07:53,970 --> 00:07:54,590
maximizing.

167
00:07:54,590 --> 00:07:58,130
So so as a simple example,
imagine that you're an

168
00:07:58,130 --> 00:08:01,120
investor in the company that's
a medium-sized company.

169
00:08:01,120 --> 00:08:03,910
And the head of that company is
jealous because all of his

170
00:08:03,910 --> 00:08:05,840
friends at bigger companies have
their own jets, and he's

171
00:08:05,840 --> 00:08:07,610
got to fly commercial.

172
00:08:07,610 --> 00:08:12,375
He says, I want my own jet,
because I'm not cool enough.

173
00:08:12,375 --> 00:08:16,370
There's this great episode of
the Simpsons where Burns goes

174
00:08:16,370 --> 00:08:17,940
to the billionaires club.

175
00:08:17,940 --> 00:08:19,130
And he's in the billionaires
club.

176
00:08:19,130 --> 00:08:21,136
And then eventually his wealth
drops so low he gets thrown

177
00:08:21,136 --> 00:08:23,020
into the millionaires club, and
it's these yokels in the

178
00:08:23,020 --> 00:08:23,580
millionaires club.

179
00:08:23,580 --> 00:08:25,970
He's like, I want to be back
in the billionaires club.

180
00:08:25,970 --> 00:08:29,980
The point is managers of
companies care about how they

181
00:08:29,980 --> 00:08:31,300
look and who they
hang out with.

182
00:08:31,300 --> 00:08:33,090
And you've got this manager of
a medium-sized company who

183
00:08:33,090 --> 00:08:33,909
wants his own private jet.

184
00:08:33,909 --> 00:08:36,820
But he knows that that's
not profit maximizing.

185
00:08:36,820 --> 00:08:39,460
Because he knows that if he
figures out his travel, and

186
00:08:39,460 --> 00:08:41,905
prices it out at competitive
prices, it'll be cheaper to

187
00:08:41,905 --> 00:08:43,270
just travel commercial.

188
00:08:43,270 --> 00:08:43,900
So what does he do?

189
00:08:43,900 --> 00:08:48,270
He puts together a glossy
PowerPoint which he presents

190
00:08:48,270 --> 00:08:51,060
to you, the owner of the
company, showing that

191
00:08:51,060 --> 00:08:54,780
financially it would be more
prudent to own a jet than to

192
00:08:54,780 --> 00:08:56,005
fly commercial.

193
00:08:56,005 --> 00:08:58,186
What he doesn't point out and
put into that PowerPoint is

194
00:08:58,186 --> 00:09:00,270
that in putting together the
commercial prices he used, he

195
00:09:00,270 --> 00:09:02,820
chose the highest rates from
flying from point A to point

196
00:09:02,820 --> 00:09:04,990
B, not the lowest rates.

197
00:09:04,990 --> 00:09:06,656
Now, unless you're an expert
on the cost of flying from

198
00:09:06,656 --> 00:09:08,010
point A to point B, you
won't know that.

199
00:09:08,010 --> 00:09:09,110
You'll say, well, that's
a pretty impressive

200
00:09:09,110 --> 00:09:09,650
presentation.

201
00:09:09,650 --> 00:09:12,640
Yes, you can show you've saved
20% by having your own plane.

202
00:09:12,640 --> 00:09:13,630
Go get it.

203
00:09:13,630 --> 00:09:15,640
But it turned out he
didn't save 20%.

204
00:09:15,640 --> 00:09:18,050
He just cooked the numbers in
a way to make his life nicer

205
00:09:18,050 --> 00:09:20,300
even if it wasn't profit
maximizing.

206
00:09:20,300 --> 00:09:23,170
And that's an example of the
kind of problem that arises

207
00:09:23,170 --> 00:09:24,420
with imperfect information.

208
00:09:24,420 --> 00:09:27,420

209
00:09:27,420 --> 00:09:29,070
And I could go through examples
all the time.

210
00:09:29,070 --> 00:09:31,470
But I think you guys probably
all understand what I'm

211
00:09:31,470 --> 00:09:33,930
talking about, which is there's
lots of ways employees

212
00:09:33,930 --> 00:09:36,290
of companies might make their
lives nicer that aren't profit

213
00:09:36,290 --> 00:09:37,300
maximizing.

214
00:09:37,300 --> 00:09:39,450
Now, corporations have
recognized this from time

215
00:09:39,450 --> 00:09:41,010
immemorial.

216
00:09:41,010 --> 00:09:43,080
And they've recognized that
their owners are too diffuse

217
00:09:43,080 --> 00:09:43,730
to monitor this.

218
00:09:43,730 --> 00:09:46,350
So what corporations do
is they have set up an

219
00:09:46,350 --> 00:09:52,430
intermediary between the owners
and the producers

220
00:09:52,430 --> 00:09:53,680
called the board of directors.

221
00:09:53,680 --> 00:09:58,710

222
00:09:58,710 --> 00:10:01,570
The board of directors is a set
of individuals appointed

223
00:10:01,570 --> 00:10:04,320
by the owners that are supposed
to actually pay

224
00:10:04,320 --> 00:10:07,040
attention to what's going
on in production.

225
00:10:07,040 --> 00:10:09,470
The owners say, look, we can't
afford to pay attention.

226
00:10:09,470 --> 00:10:11,350
But we're going to appoint you,
the board of directors,

227
00:10:11,350 --> 00:10:12,510
and we're going to pay you
quite a lot of money.

228
00:10:12,510 --> 00:10:15,460
A typical director on the
Fortune 500 company will make

229
00:10:15,460 --> 00:10:17,770
$100,000 plus a year.

230
00:10:17,770 --> 00:10:20,330
It's a part-time job.

231
00:10:20,330 --> 00:10:22,120
We appointed you to keep
an eye on the tools of

232
00:10:22,120 --> 00:10:22,850
production.

233
00:10:22,850 --> 00:10:24,470
The problem is the board
of directors aren't

234
00:10:24,470 --> 00:10:25,180
that good at it either.

235
00:10:25,180 --> 00:10:27,880
Because it turns out to be
really hard to figure out

236
00:10:27,880 --> 00:10:30,600
exactly what's going on.

237
00:10:30,600 --> 00:10:33,240
And this is made worse, because
the members of the

238
00:10:33,240 --> 00:10:35,560
board of directors are often
chosen by management of the

239
00:10:35,560 --> 00:10:37,900
company, by the people
running the

240
00:10:37,900 --> 00:10:39,650
production, not by the owners.

241
00:10:39,650 --> 00:10:42,190
So they'll make selections of
who's going to be on the board

242
00:10:42,190 --> 00:10:42,720
of directors.

243
00:10:42,720 --> 00:10:43,885
And they'll pack it with
their friends who

244
00:10:43,885 --> 00:10:45,040
will be nice to them.

245
00:10:45,040 --> 00:10:49,010
So, for example, Richard Grasso
was the CEO of the New

246
00:10:49,010 --> 00:10:50,610
York Stock Exchange.

247
00:10:50,610 --> 00:10:53,320
He started out in the mail
room, worked his way up.

248
00:10:53,320 --> 00:10:55,290
He became CEO of the New York
Stock Exchange and retired

249
00:10:55,290 --> 00:10:59,120
with $187 million severance
package which was outrageous

